      {
        "id": 3049254,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-12-17T00:54:07.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"160094\">\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=3377385&amp;iNote=8830467\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>2012 Delamotte Champagne Blanc de Blancs Mill\u00e9sim\u00e9</strong></a> <em>- France, Champagne (11/6/2020)</em><br>\n\u2013 tasted non-blind over approx. 1.5 hours \u2013</p>\n<p>NOSE: Light and airy; mango; kiwi fruit.</p>\n<p>BODY: light bodied; airy mouthfeel.</p>\n<p>TASTE: high acidity; crisp; a touch creamy (oaky?); bit of mango. Overall, quite nice \u2014 a bit reserved today, but seems to have the stuffing to develop nicely over the short term. I subsequently purchased three more bottles. Gut impression score: low 90s.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>No oak in Salon, Delamotte or any of the Laurent-Perrier wines, which are all made more or less the same way. What you\u2019re picking up is lees contact / liqueur d\u2019expedition / the interactions between the byproducts of the former with the latter in bottle.</p>",
